Anise Biscotti
Biscotti is a classic Italian treat that’s beloved around the world and it never
fails to hit the mark. It’s fun, tasty, and adaptable, and there’s nothing better
than making these at home. Biscotti is perfect with coffee or if you’re
looking for a lighter dessert. Better still, anise biscotti is just gorgeous.
Anise has a very distinct licorice flavor profile and it’s really beautiful. It’s
sweet but not overpowering and great for those who love bold flavors.
Serving Size: 10-12
Cooking Time: 40 Minutes
Ingredients:
¾ cup of soft butter
2 ¾ cups of all-purpose flour
2 teaspoons of crushed anise seeds
5 teaspoons of baking powder
3 eggs
1 ¼ cup of sugar
1 ¼ cup of almonds
1 tablespoon of milk
1 teaspoon of anise extract
¼ teaspoon of vanilla extract
½ teaspoon of nutmeg
½ teaspoon of cinnamon
¼ teaspoon of salt
Instructions:
1. Add the almonds to a skillet and toast them gently at a low-tomedium heat for 10 minutes. It’s important to stir and move
them often so they don’t burn. Once toasted, remove the
almonds from the heat and set them on a chopping board to
cool down for a few minutes, then chop them finely.
2. Preheat your oven to 375 degrees Fahrenheit and line 2
baking sheets with parchment paper or silicone cooking mats.
3. In a bowl, combine nutmeg with flour, cinnamon, salt, baking
powder, and anise seeds, then set the mixture aside for a few
minutes.
4. To a stand mixer, add the butter and 1 cup of sugar, then
cream them for 2-3 minutes or until they’re nice and fluffy.
Crack each egg into the mixer then add the vanilla extract and
anise extract and beat them for a further 30-40 seconds until
they’re incorporated into the butter mixture.
5. Add the almonds and flour mixture to the stand mixer and
combine them until a dough forms.
6. Split the dough into 2 pieces and shape them into semi-thick
large squares. Ideally, you want each piece of dough to be of
equal size and weight otherwise cooking times might vary.
7. Put each piece of dough onto a baking sheet then brush them
with milk and sprinkle the remaining sugar on top. Place the
biscotti into the oven to bake for 12-15 minutes.
8. Remove the biscotti from the oven (and remove them from
the baking sheets too) and set them on a cooling rack for 20
minutes. Reduce your oven to 300 degrees Fahrenheit then
slice the biscotti into rectangles and bake them for a further 8
minutes.
9. Once crispy, remove the biscotti from the oven and let them
cool down for 30 minutes before serving.
